 emissions from the plants, and those costs are expected to increase further over the remaining term of the agreements. TransCanada’s contract with Sundance A wasn’t set to expire until 2017, and Sundance B and Sheerness contracts were set to end in 2020. No new timelines have been confirmed yet.\nWith the plants set for retirement, Parkland County Mayor Rod Shaigec said this will mean the county will be taking a huge hit financially. The county is currently receiving just over $12 million a year in tax revenue from Sundance, Keephills and other mining activity.\nMore importantly, he said, is the impact it will have on employment. He noted re-employment is made even more difficult for many of the individuals affected, as the majority of them don’t have post-secondary education and are over 50 years old.\n“There’s going to be limited opportunity for them once these plants are phased out, and that’s going to take money out of the community as well,” Shaigec said, adding many will likely leave the area.\nRobin Campbell, the president of the Coal Association of Canada and former West Yellowhead MLA, said there has been a sense of uncertainty among the people in each of the communities — from the loss of employment to real estate values.\n“The families and the people that work in the industry really feel that they’re being short-changed by this,” he stated. “Some of these people have been working at the mines or at the plants for quite a while and are well-established in their communities and are now looking at maybe having to move their families.”\nThe CAC wants to see money invested in research technology to continue improving coal technology.\n“We’re not arguing climate change and we’re not arguing greenhouse gas, but we are saying that over the years you’ve seen a very positive transition in coal technology,” Campbell stated. “You look at the plants around Wabamun, the air quality is good. People in those mines take pride in that.”\nAlbertans, and Canadians, have the ability to take the lead in research and technology and providing the world with clean coal technology that could help many underdeveloped countries, he said.\n“It’s a good, stable, affordable energy source in the province,” Campbell said of the 37 billion tons of coal found in Alberta.\nHe added it is “a very viable part of the Alberta economy,” which supplies affordable power to residents — especially those on a fixed income.\nWhile there has been a push for renewable energy, there is uncertainty as to what it would cost, Campbell said.\n“Residents, small businesses — (and) right now some of them are hanging on by a thread — can’t afford any hiccups in their utility bills,” he stated.\nAlbertans will be paying the cost to phase out coal — and its not going to be cheap, Campbell emphasized.\nThe plan doesn’t bode well for communities such as Forestburg and Hanna he said.\n“A lot of these communities are based on the fact that the power plant is there and the mine is there. Without that, some of these communities could really suffer,” Campbell said.\nLocally, Stony Plain Mayor William Choy said there are about 300 jobs related to the coal industry and another 400 directly related. Changes will mean finding a way to re-employ these people.\n“It’s a lot of fear of what’s going to happen in the future,” Choy said of those whose jobs could be impacted.\n“The question still out there is why? We already have a climate change plan in place by the federal government and agreed upon by the provincial government where it calls for decommissioning of older plants. So why cost taxpayers billions of dollars to accelerate that?”\nShaigec noted there is recognition of the need for industries and individuals to do a better job of minimizing their environmental footprint. But when it comes to the phase-out plan, all the consequences need to be considered.\n“There’s going to be considerable factors that I believe haven’t been considered, and (there needs to be) dialogue with all the stakeholders,” Shaigec stated. “Make everybody aware of what the financial costs and implications are going to be on individuals, families, businesses and all levels of government as well.”\nThe CAC is asking coal workers, municipalities, businesses and residents to voice their concerns to their MLA, the minister of environment and Premier Rachel Notley.\n“The government has to sit down with coal mining communities and talk to them and explain what the plan is and how the workers fit into those plans,” Campbell said. “It’s about getting answers for hard-working Albertans that are being penalized because they work in coal.”\nmlove@postmedia.com\nTwitter: @MarciaTheLovely \n","keywords":[{"relevance":"0.971923","sentiment":{"mixed":"1","score":"0.0194177","type":"positive"},"keywords_text":"coal"},{"relevance":"0.865662","sentiment":{"score":"0.314837","type":"positive"},"keywords_text":"coal industry"},{"relevance":"0.826167","sentiment":{"type":"neutral"},"keywords_text":"coal technology"},{"relevance":"0.815294","sentiment":{"type":"neutral"},"keywords_text":"coal industry employees"},{"relevance":"0.787802","sentiment":{"type":"neutral"},"keywords_text":"Coal Association"},{"relevance":"0.769803","sentiment":{"mixed":"1","score":"0.0633428","type":"positive"},"keywords_text":"Parkland County"},{"relevance":"0.752812","sentiment":{"type":"neutral"},"keywords_text":"clean coal technology"},{"relevance":"0.750776","sentiment":{"type":"neutral"},"keywords_text":"coal mining communities"},{"relevance":"0.688786","sentiment":{"score":"-0.246462","type":"negative"},"keywords_text":"power generation plants"},{"relevance":"0.67221","sentiment":{"type":"neutral"},"keywords_text":"Climate Leadership Plan"},{"relevance":"0.662676","sentiment":{"type":"neutral"},"keywords_text":"Stony Plain"},{"relevance":"0.661758","sentiment":{"score":"0.422589","type":"positive"},"keywords_text":"Sheerness power plant"},{"relevance":"0.656782","sentiment":{"score":"0.442976","type":"positi